<section xml:id="section-factoring-trinomials-when-a-is-one">

    <title>Factoring Trinomials when <m>a=1</m></title>

    <introduction>
        <p>In the last chapter, we learned how to multiply binomials like <m>(x+2)(x+3)=x^2+5x+6</m>. In this section, we will learn how to go backward and do <m>x^2+5x+6=(x+2)(x+3)</m>. We will first learn how to factor trinomial <m>ax^2+bx+c</m> where <m>a=1</m>.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="6SACul2TFEM" width="70%"/>
            <video youtube="_Wb_CT-1VN8" width="70%"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Factoring Trinomials by Listing Factor Pairs</title>

        <p>In <m>x^2+5x+6=(x+2)(x+3)</m>, notice that <m>2+3=5</m> and <m>2\cdot3=6</m>. In general, we have<me>x^2+(a+b)x+ab=(x+a)(x+b)</me>For example, when we factor<me>x^2+13x+40=(x+?)(x+?)</me>we are looking for two numbers, whose product is 40, and whose sum is 13. We will list all factor pairs of <m>40</m> and find a pair whose sum is <m>13</m>:</p>

        <table xml:id="table-positive-factor-pair-of-forty">
            <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>40</m></caption>
            <tabular>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <col halign="center"/>
                <row bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                    <cell>Sum</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1\cdot40</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>41</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2\cdot20</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>22</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>4\cdot10</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>14</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>5\cdot8</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>13</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>To avoid missing factor pairs, we started from <m>1</m>, and went up one by one. Although <m>3</m> doesn't go into <m>40</m> evenly, we must try it, so we don't miss any factor pairs. We stopped as soon as we found <m>5</m> and <m>8</m>, whose sum is <m>13</m>. The solution is<me>x^2+13x+40=(x+5)(x+8)</me>Let's look at a few more examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>y^2-13y+40</m>.</p>

                <p>We still look for factor pairs in <xref ref="table-positive-factor-pair-of-forty">Table</xref>. We see <m>5</m> and <m>8</m> is a factor pair, and <m>5+8=13</m>, but we are looking for a pair whose sum is <m>-13</m>. We need to realize that <m>-5</m> and <m>-8</m> also make a factor pair of <m>40</m>, as <m>(-5)(-8)=40</m>. We should modify <xref ref="table-positive-factor-pair-of-forty">Table</xref> in this way:</p>

                <table xml:id="table-factor-pair-of-forty">
                    <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>40</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1\cdot40</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>41</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1)\cdot(-40)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-41</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2\cdot20</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>22</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2)\cdot(-20)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-22</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell>n/a</cell>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>4\cdot10</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>14</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-4)\cdot(-10)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-14</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>5\cdot8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>13</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-5)\cdot(-8)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-13</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>Solution: <m>y^2-13y+40=(y-5)(y-8)</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <p>For each factor pair, we should list two pairs. For <m>5\cdot8</m>, we should also list <m>(-5)\cdot(-8)=40</m>. In a different problem, for <m>5\cdot(-8)=-40</m>, we should also list <m>(-5)\cdot8=-40</m>.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>z^2-3z-40</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will list all factor pairs of <m>-40</m>, and look for a pair whose sum is <m>-3</m>.</p>

                <table>
                    <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>-40</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1\cdot(-40)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-39</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1)\cdot40</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>39</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2\cdot(-20)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-18</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2)\cdot20</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>18</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell>n/a</cell>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>4\cdot(-10)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-4)\cdot10</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>5\cdot(-8)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell>...</cell>
                            <cell>...</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>From the table, we found the factor pair <m>5</m> and <m>-8</m>, whose sum is <m>-3</m>. The solution is <m>z^2-3z-40=(z+5)(z-8)</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>m^2-2m-40</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will list all factor pairs of <m>-40</m>, and look for a pair whose sum is <m>-2</m>.</p>

                <table xml:id="table-factor-pair-of-negative-forty">
                    <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>-40</m></caption>
                    <tabular>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <col halign="center"/>
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                            <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                            <cell>Sum</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>1\cdot(-40)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-39</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-1)\cdot40</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>39</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>2\cdot(-20)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-18</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-2)\cdot20</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>18</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell>n/a</cell>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>4\cdot(-10)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-4)\cdot10</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>5\cdot(-8)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>(-5)\cdot8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                            <cell>n/a</cell>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                            <cell>n/a</cell>
                            <cell/>
                            <cell/>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>8\cdot(-5)</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-40</m></cell>
                            <cell>...</cell>
                            <cell>...</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>Note that we stopped at <m>8\cdot(-5)</m>, because we already found this pair earlier. Once we find a duplicate pair, we can stop, because all later pairs would be duplicates.</p>

                <p>We listed all factor pairs of <m>-40</m>, but no pair's sum is <m>-2</m>. We say the trinomial <m>m^2-2m-40</m> is prime, just like prime numbers which cannot be factored.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Once we can factor a basic trinomial like <m>x^2+13x+40=(x+5)(x+8)</m>, we can factor some variations:<md>
            <mrow>x^2+13x+40\amp=(x+5)(x+8)</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+13xy+40y^2\amp=(x+5y)(x+8y)</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2y^2+13xy+40\amp=(xy+5)(xy+8)</mrow>
        </md></p>

    </subsection>

