    <subsection>
        <title>Factoring Trinomials by the AC Method</title>

        <p>The Listing Factor Pairs Method is the most efficient method to factor trinomials <m>ax^2+bx+c</m> when <m>a=1</m>. In later sections, we will learn how to factor trinomials when <m>a\ne1</m>, and the List Factor Pairs Method will not work any more. We will learn the <term>AC Method</term> and <term>Generic Rectangle Method</term>, which will be useful when <m>a\ne1</m>. Those two methods also work when <m>a=1</m>, although they are not as efficient as the Listing Factor Pairs Method.</p>

        <p>One method to multiply the binomials <m>(x+5)(x+8)</m> is to first distribute <m>(x+5)</m> into <m>(x+8)</m>, and then distribute again:<md>
            <mrow>(x+5)(x+8)\amp=x(x+5)+8(x+5)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=x^2+5x+8x+40</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=x^2+13x+40</mrow>
        </md></p>

        <p>The AC Method follows the exact steps backward, going from <m>x^2+13x+40</m> back to <m>(x+5)(x+8)</m>.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>x^2+13x+40</m> with the AC Method.</p>

                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Step 1: We treat <m>x^2+13x+40</m> as <m>ax^2+bx+c</m>, and we have <m>a=1, b=13</m> and <m>c=40</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 2: We find the product of <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> (thus the name AC Method), and we have <m>ac=(1)(40)=40</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 3: List all factor pairs of the product <m>40</m> until we find a pair whose sum is <m>b</m>'s value, <m>13</m>. By <xref ref="table-factor-pair-of-forty">Table</xref>, that pair is <m>5</m> and <m>8</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 4: In <m>x^2+13x+40</m>, break the second term <m>13x</m> into <m>5x</m> and <m>8x</m>, and then factor by grouping:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>x^2+13x+40\amp=x^2+5x+8x+40</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=x(x+5)+8(x+5)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=(x+5)(x+8)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>y^2-3yz-40z^2</m> with the AC Method.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Step 1: We treat <m>y^2-3yz-40z^2</m> as <m>ay^2+byz+cz^2</m>, and we have <m>a=1, b=-3</m> and <m>c=-40</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 2: We find the product of <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> (thus the name AC Method), and we have <m>ac=(1)(-40)=-40</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 3: List all factor pairs of the product <m>-40</m> until we find a pair whose sum is <m>b</m>'s value, <m>-3</m>. By <xref ref="table-factor-pair-of-negative-forty">Table</xref>, that pair is <m>5</m> and <m>-8</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 4: In <m>y^2-3yz-40z^2</m>, break the second term <m>-3yz</m> into <m>5yz</m> and <m>-8yz</m>, and then factor by grouping:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>y^2-3yz-40z^2\amp=y^2+5yz-8yz-40z^2</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=y(y+5z)-8z(y+5z)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=(y+5z)(y-8z)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

